## Step-by-Step Setup {#step-by-step}

### STEP 1: Generate GitHub Personal Access Token

#### 1.1 Go to GitHub Settings

```
GitHub Account → Settings
→ Developer settings
→ Personal access tokens
→ Tokens (classic)
→ Generate new token
```

#### 1.2 Configure Token Scopes

```
Token name: jenkins-ci

Scopes to select:
  ✓ repo (Full control of private repositories)
  ✓ admin:repo_hook (Full control of repo hooks)
  ✓ admin:org_hook (Full control of org hooks)
  ✓ user:email (Access email addresses)

Expiration: 90 days (or your preference)
```

#### 1.3 Generate and Copy Token

```
Click "Generate token"
→ Copy the token immediately
→ Save it somewhere safe

⚠️ You won't see it again!
```

---

### STEP 2: Add GitHub Credentials to Jenkins

#### 2.1 Access Jenkins Credentials

```
Jenkins Home
→ Manage Jenkins
→ Manage Credentials
→ System (on left)
→ Global credentials (unrestricted)
```

#### 2.2 Add New Credentials

```
Click "Add Credentials" (top right)
```

#### 2.3 Fill in Credential Details

```
Kind: Username with password

Username: 
  your_github_username
  (Example: john-dev)

Password: 
  <paste_your_github_token>
  (The long token you copied)

ID: 
  github-credentials
  (This is the name Jenkins will use)

Description: 
  GitHub Personal Access Token

→ Click "Create"
```

---

### STEP 3: Create Jenkins Job

#### 3.1 Create New Job

```
Jenkins Home Page
→ Click "New Item" (left sidebar)
→ Enter Job Name: "my-app-ci"
→ Select "Pipeline"
→ Click "OK"
```

#### 3.2 Configure General Settings

```
GENERAL TAB:

Description: 
  "CI/CD Pipeline for My App"

☑ GitHub project

Project url: 
  https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/YOUR_REPO
  
  Example: https://github.com/john-dev/my-app
```

#### 3.3 Configure Build Triggers

```
BUILD TRIGGERS TAB:

☑ GitHub hook trigger for GITScm polling

(This allows GitHub webhook to trigger the job)
```

#### 3.4 Configure Pipeline

```
PIPELINE TAB:

Definition: 
  Select "Pipeline script from SCM"

SCM:
  Select "Git"

Repository URL:
  https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/YOUR_REPO.git
  
  Example: https://github.com/john-dev/my-app.git

Credentials:
  Select "github-credentials" (from dropdown)

Branch Specifier:
  */main
  
  (or */develop if you use develop branch)

Script Path:
  Jenkinsfile
  
  (Jenkins looks for Jenkinsfile in repo root)
```

#### 3.5 Save Job

```
Scroll down and click "Save"

Your Jenkins job is now created!
```

---

### STEP 4: Add Webhook to GitHub

#### 4.1 Go to GitHub Repo Settings

```
Open Your Repository on GitHub
→ Click "Settings" (top right)
→ Left sidebar: Click "Webhooks"
```

#### 4.2 Add New Webhook

```
Click "Add webhook" button (top right)
```

#### 4.3 Fill Webhook Details

```
Payload URL: *
  http://YOUR_JENKINS_SERVER:8080/github-webhook/
  
  Examples:
  - http://jenkins.company.com:8080/github-webhook/
  - http://192.168.1.100:8080/github-webhook/
  - http://localhost:8080/github-webhook/ (if local)

Content type: *
  Select "application/json"

Secret:
  Leave EMPTY (not required)

Which events would you like to trigger this webhook? *
  ☑ Just the push event (default)
  OR
  ☑ Let me select individual events
    - Push events ✓
    - Pull requests ✓

Active:
  ✓ Check to make webhook active
```

#### 4.4 Save Webhook

```
Click "Add webhook" button (bottom right)

You should see:
✓ Green checkmark = Webhook added successfully
```

#### 4.5 Verify Webhook

```
On Webhooks page:
→ Find your webhook in list
→ Click on it
→ Click "Recent Deliveries" tab

You should see:
✓ Green checkmark = Success
✗ Red X = Failed

If failed:
  → Click delivery to see error
  → Check Jenkins URL is correct
  → Check Jenkins is running
```

